Accessing the csv file within the .tar.gz file¶

To enable reproducibility without having to manually download just the tar.gz 1) clone the hiring-challenges repository from git bash (git clone https://github.com/DoodleScheduling/hiring-challenges.git) 2) store the absolute path of the '.tar.gz' file in a variable 3) extract that variable(tar.gz) file 4) Saving the corresponding csv file in a pandas dataframe
In [2]:
tar_path = os.path.abspath(r'adventure_works_purchase_orders.tar.gz')
tar = tarfile.open(tar_path,
                   mode='r')
tar.extractall()
tar.close()
df_1 = pd.read_csv('adventure_works_purchase_orders.csv')

In [23]:
df_1['unit_final_price'] = (df_1['unit_price']*(1-df_1['unit_price_discount'])).round(2)
df_1['final_order_price'] = df_1['order_qty'] * df_1['unit_final_price']
In [24]:
## Calculating Unit and Order margins

### Unit Margins 
## Margin I includes granted Discount but not the Freight Cost 
df_1['unit_margin_1'] = df_1['unit_final_price'] - df_1['unit_cost']
df_1['unit_cm1%'] = df_1['unit_margin_1']/df_1['unit_final_price']

## Margin II includes Discount and Freight Cost
df_1['unit_margin_2'] = df_1['unit_margin_1']- df_1['unit_freight_cost']
df_1['unit_cm2_%'] = df_1['unit_margin_2']/df_1['unit_final_price']

### Order Margins
df_1['order_margin_1'] = df_1['final_order_price'] - df_1['order_cost']
df_1['order_cm1%'] = df_1['order_margin_1']/df_1['final_order_price']

df_1['order_margin_2'] = df_1['order_margin_1'] - df_1['order_freight_cost']
df_1['order_cm2%'] = df_1['order_margin_2']/df_1['final_order_price']

Contribution Margin I (CM I) is calculated by removing the COGS and the discount from the Final Revenue made Contribution Margin II (CM II) is calculated by additionally removing fulfillment costs, as are the freight costs

## Changing some default matplotlib paramters
### Did this in retrospect after realizing the writing would be too small
matplotlib.rcParams['font.size'] = 12
def pie_plot(source_df, x_parameter, _labels, title):
    plt.figure(figsize = (16,8))
    plt.pie(source_df[x_parameter], labels = source_df[_labels],
           autopct='%1.1f%%');
    plt.title(title, fontsize = 12);

Function to aggregate in given groupings incl. at least a ideally monthly view¶

In [57]:
def aggregate_grouped_df(df_name, grouping):

    """
    In the grouping variable, if using more than 1, please enter 'order_month' or the relevant time period first 
    for the relevant delta columns to be created
        
    """
    ## Nice to add in the future - function that rearranges the variables in the list to put the time_bound variable first
    new_df = df_name.groupby(grouping).agg({'order_qty':[np.mean, np.sum], 'sales_order_number':'count',
                                  'order_price':[np.mean, np.sum], 'final_order_price':[np.mean, np.sum], 
                                  'order_cost':[np.mean, np.sum],'order_freight_cost':[np.mean, np.sum],
                                  'order_margin_1':'sum', 'order_margin_2':'sum', 
                                  'unit_price':'mean', 'unit_cost':'mean'}).reset_index()
    
    
   
    #### Converting MultiIndex to a conventional index for ease of use
    ### Renaming columns for ease of use
    
    new_df.columns = new_df.columns.to_flat_index()
    new_df = new_df.rename(columns={('order_month',''):'order_month', 
                  ('order_qty', 'mean'):'items_ordered_mean', ('order_qty', 'sum'):'items_ordered_sum',
                  ('sales_order_number', 'count'): 'unique_orders', ('order_price', 'mean'): 'revenue_mean',
                  ('order_price', 'sum'): 'revenue_sum',    ('final_order_price', 'mean'): 'final_revenue_mean',
                  ('final_order_price', 'sum'): 'final_revenue_sum', ('order_cost', 'mean'): 'order_cost_mean',
                  ('order_cost', 'sum'): 'order_cost_sum',  ('order_freight_cost', 'mean'): 'order_freight_cost_mean',
                  ('order_freight_cost', 'sum') : 'order_freight_cost_sum', 
                  ('order_margin_1', 'sum'): 'order_margin_1_sum', ('order_margin_2', 'sum') : 'order_margin_2_sum',
                  ('unit_price', 'mean'):'unit_price_mean', ('unit_cost', 'mean'):'unit_cost_mean'})
    
    if isinstance(grouping, list):
        
        for element in grouping[1:]:

#            renaming every other column in the grouping  
            new_df = new_df.rename(columns={(element, ''):element})
        
        grouping_use = grouping[1:]
        if len(grouping_use) == 1:
            grouping_use = str(grouping_use).strip("[]''")
    else: 
        grouping_use = grouping
        
    ## Calculating Delta columns
    new_df['revenue_sum_delta'] = new_df.groupby(grouping_use)['revenue_sum'].diff()
    new_df['revenue_sum_delta_pct'] = new_df.groupby(grouping_use)['revenue_sum'].pct_change()

    new_df['final_revenue_sum_delta'] = new_df.groupby(grouping_use)['final_revenue_sum'].diff()
    new_df['final_revenue_sum_delta_pct'] = new_df.groupby(grouping_use)['final_revenue_sum'].pct_change()

    new_df['order_cost_sum_delta'] = new_df.groupby(grouping_use)['order_cost_sum'].diff()
    new_df['order_cost_sum_delta_pct'] = new_df.groupby(grouping_use)['order_cost_sum'].pct_change()

    new_df['order_freight_cost_sum_delta'] = new_df.groupby(grouping_use)['order_freight_cost_sum'].diff()
    new_df['order_freight_cost_sum_delta_pct'] = new_df.groupby(grouping_use)['order_freight_cost_sum'].pct_change()

    new_df['order_margin_1_sum_delta'] = new_df.groupby(grouping_use)['order_margin_1_sum'].diff()
    new_df['order_margin_1_sum_delta_pct'] = new_df.groupby(grouping_use)['order_margin_1_sum'].pct_change()

    new_df['order_margin_2_sum_delta'] = new_df.groupby(grouping_use)['order_margin_2_sum'].diff()
    new_df['order_margin_2_sum_delta_pct'] = new_df.groupby(grouping_use)['order_margin_2_sum'].pct_change()
    
    ## Calculating other possibly relevant columns
    new_df['order_discount_sum'] = new_df['final_revenue_sum'] - new_df['revenue_sum']
    
    new_df['cogs/revenue'] = new_df['order_cost_sum']/new_df['revenue_sum']
    new_df['cogs/final_revenue'] = new_df['order_cost_sum']/new_df['final_revenue_sum']
    
    new_df['order_cm1%'] = new_df['order_margin_1_sum']/new_df['revenue_sum']
    new_df['order_cm2%'] = new_df['order_margin_2_sum']/new_df['revenue_sum']
    
    return new_df

In [67]:
def plot_variable_over_time(df_to_plot, variable_to_plot, variable_ext_name, hue_to_differentiate,
                            hue_ext_name, variable_type='absolute'): 
    """ 
    Function is meant to plot development of variable by month only.
    Variable_type should either be 'percentual' or 'absolute'. It is absolute by default
    """
    plt.figure(figsize = (16,8))

    ax = plt.axes()
    ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MultipleLocator(2.5))

    sns.lineplot('order_month', variable_to_plot, 
                 hue = hue_to_differentiate, data = df_to_plot)

    plt.title(variable_ext_name + " over time by "+ hue_ext_name);
    
    if variable_type == 'percentual':
        plt.ylim(0, 1);
        
    ## enabling a YoY comparison that makes sense
    if hue_to_differentiate == 'order_year':
        ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MultipleLocator(1))
        plt.xlim(1, 12)
    
    plt.xlabel('Order Month', fontsize = 12);
    plt.ylabel(variable_ext_name, fontsize = 12);
